==External links== *{{Official|http://www.ace-game.jp/}} {{ja icon}} {{portal bar|Video games|2010s}} {{FromSoftware games}}
[[Category:2011 video games]] [[Category:Action video games]] [[Category:Banpresto games]] [[Category:Crossover video games]] [[Category:FromSoftware games]] [[Category:Japan-exclusive video games]] [[Category:Mecha video games]] [[Category:PlayStation Portable games]] [[Category:PlayStation Portable-only games]] [[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]

An '''antimasque''' (also spelled '''antemasque''') is a comic or [[grotesque dance]] presented before or between the acts of a [[masque]], a type of dramatic composition.<ref>{{cite book|title=Collins English Dictionary|date=2012|publisher=William Collins Sons & Co. Ltd|edition=Digital|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/antimasque|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> The antimasque is a spectacle of disorder which usually starts or precedes the masque itself and was played by professional actors while members of the court primarily performed the roles of the masque.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Best|first1=Michael|title=The antimasque|url=http://internetshakespeare.uvic.ca/Library/SLT/stage/masques/antimasque.html|website=Shakespeare's Life and Times|publisher=University of Victoria|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> It is characterized by impropriety and is transformed by the masque into goodness, propriety, and order, typically by the King's presence alone.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Astington|first1=John|title=English Court Theatre 1558 -1642|date=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-64065-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f9EJ7Re8Pe0C&pg=PA155&lpg=PA155&dq=ballet+grotesque&source=bl&ots=oDtr2Oxgge&sig=AaYViXHavhGlKTGQ4SHUslYFaRs&hl=en&ei=FVRFTaCmNoGKhQfY8ajeAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=9&ved=0CDsQ6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=antimasque&f=false|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref>  It was also contrasted with the masque by the use of the lower class as characters.<ref name="Encyclopædia Britannica">{{cite web|title=masque (entertainment)|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/368090/masque#ref141490|website=Encyclopædia Britannica|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> This then was supposed to harmonize with the king and the higher class.
In later years, the antimasque developed into a [[farce]] or [[pantomime]].<ref name="Encyclopædia Britannica" /> The concept of the antemasque, or anti-masque, was conceived by [[Ben Jonson]].<ref>Eras of the dance: the George Verdak Collection,  Montgomery Museum of Fine Arts, Huntsville Museum of Art - 1976 "The antemasque was an innovation by Jonson which introduced the grotesque or antic element to the performance which preceded the masque proper. The antemasque differed from the masque in that it was performed by professionals .."</ref>  Masques originally usually had one antemasque before the main masque, but later it became common to have several antemasques preceding the main masque.<ref>''Thomas Middleton: The Collected Works'' 2010 p.1324 0199580537   "Earlier masques usually had one antemasque, which preceded the main masque, but later it became common for the masques to have several antemasques."</ref><ref>Mara R. Wade ''Gender Matters: Discourses of Violence in Early Modern Literature'' 9401210233 - 2013 "This moment, along with the antemasque's inclusion of the marriage god Hymen, recalls Ben Jonson's The Masque of Hymen (1606), in which Juno and eight ladies descend from above. Bianca adopts another common feature of Jonson's ..."</ref>

