{{For|the skate brand of the same name|Roller Derby (brand)}} {{Infobox sport | name=Roller derby | image=WasatchVsJunctionCity.jpg | caption= A roller derby scrimmage in Utah. | union=[[Women's Flat Track Derby Association|WFTDA]], [[Men's Roller Derby Association|MRDA]], [[Junior roller derby|JRDA]], [[Fédération Internationale de Roller Sports|FIRS]] | nickname= Derby | first= 1935, [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] | registered= | clubs= 4,700+ | contact= Yes | team= 15 on roster, up to 5 on track during each jam.<ref name="WFTDARules" /> | mgender= | category= Indoor, [[roller sport]] | equipment= [[Roller skates]], [[helmet]], [[knee pad]]s, [[elbow pad]]s, [[wrist guard]]s, [[mouthguard]] | venue= [[Roller rink]] | olympic= No }}
'''Roller derby''' is a [[contact sport]] played by two teams of five members [[roller skating]] counter-clockwise around a track. Roller derby is played by approximately 1,250 [[amateur]] leagues worldwide, mostly inside the [[United States]].<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite news|last=Moffett |first=Matt |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324610504578278171721339976?fb_action_ids=10152543496805385&fb_action_types=og.recommends&fb_source=aggregation&fb_aggregation_id=288381481237582 |title=As the World Turns, So Do the Wheels of Roller Derby |website=Online.wsj.com |date=2013-02-03|accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref>
Game play consists of a series of short match-ups (jams) in which both teams designate a jammer (who wears a star on the helmet). The jammer scores points by lapping members of the opposing team. The teams attempt to hinder the opposing jammer while assisting their own jammer—in effect, playing both [[offense (sports)|offense]] and [[defense (sports)|defense]] simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EnFddETifY8 |title=Common Ground: the alternative sport of roller derby |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref>
While the sport has its origins in the banked-track roller-skating marathons of the 1930s, [[Leo Seltzer]] and [[Damon Runyon]] are credited with evolving the sport to its competitive form. Professional roller derby quickly became popular; in 1940, more than 5 million spectators watched in about 50 American cities. In the ensuing decades, however, it predominantly became a form of [[sports entertainment]], where theatrical elements overshadowed athleticism. Gratuitous showmanship largely ended with the sport's grassroots revival in the first decade of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D01D520xcws |title=Roller Derby: The Fastest Growing Sport In America |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2012-02-26 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref> Although roller derby retains some sports entertainment qualities such as player pseudonyms and colorful uniforms, it has abandoned scripted bouts with predetermined winners.<ref>Neale, Rick (24 June 2008). [https://www.usatoday.com/life/lifestyle/2008-06-17-female-roller-derby_N.htm "All-Female Roller Derby Elbows Its Way In as a Legitimate Sport"], ''[[USA Today]]''</ref>
Modern roller derby is an international sport, mostly played by amateurs. Most teams are all-female teams, but there is a growing number of male, unisex, and [[junior roller derby]] teams. It was under consideration as a [[roller sport]] for the [[2020 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/07/04/will-roller-derby-be-included-in-the-2020-olympics/ |title=Will roller derby be included in the 2020 Olympics? &#124; Olympics &#124; Sports &#124; National Post |website=Sports.nationalpost.com |date=4 July 2011 |accessdate=6 March 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120720053434/http://sports.nationalpost.com/2011/07/04/will-roller-derby-be-included-in-the-2020-olympics/ |archive-date=20 July 2012 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://olympictalk.nbcsports.com/2013/05/28/roller-sports-pitch-for-the-2020-olympics/|title=Roller Sports’s pitch for the 2020 Olympics|date=2013-05-28|website=Olympictalk.nbcsports.com|accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/05/30/three-sports-make-olympic-cut-for-2020-summer-games |title=Three Sports Make Olympic Cut for 2020 Summer Games |author=Greg Otto|publisher=U.S. News|date=2013-05-30|accessdate=2017-09-11 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815102732/https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/05/30/three-sports-make-olympic-cut-for-2020-summer-games |archivedate=2017-08-15}} </ref> [[Fédération Internationale de Roller Sports|FIRS]], recognized by the [[International Olympic Committee]] as the official international governing body of roller sports, released its first set of Roller Derby Rules for the World Roller Games that took place September 2017 in Nanjing, China. Most modern leagues (and their back-office volunteers) share a strong [[DIY ethic|"do-it-yourself" ethic]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fragglepuss.wordpress.com/2012/08/29/spudtown-knockdown-3-an-interview-with-candyman-tournament-director/ |title=SpudTown Knockdown 3: An Interview with CandyMan, Tournament Director &#124; Fragglepuss |website=Fragglepuss.wordpress.com |date=2012-08-29 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref> that combines athleticism with the styles of [[Punk fashion|punk]] and [[Camp (style)|camp]].<ref name=Fagundes>{{cite web|url=https://papers.ssrn.com/abstract=1755305|title=Talk Derby to Me: Intellectual Property Norms Governing Roller Derby Pseudonyms|first=Dave|last=Fagundes|date=2011-03-15|accessdate=2018-06-30|website=Papers.ssrn.com}}</ref> {{As of|2018}}, the [[Women's Flat Track Derby Association]] (WFTDA) had 423 full member leagues and 46 apprentice leagues.<ref name="WFTDA Member Leagues" />
==Rules== [[File:CharmvsRivet2639463631 aee9fd553e.jpg|thumb|left|A [[Charm City Roller Girls|Charm City All Stars]] ([[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]]) blocker vs. a Rhode Island Riveter ([[Providence, RI|Providence]], [[Rhode Island]]) jammer]] Contemporary roller derby has a basic set of rules, with variations reflecting the interests of a [[#Associations and governing bodies|governing body]]'s member leagues. The summary below is based on the rules of the Women's Flat Track Derby Association (WFTDA).<ref name="WFTDARules">{{cite web|title=The Rules of Flat Track Roller Derby|url=https://rules.wftda.com/|publisher=Women's Flat Track Derby Association (WFTDA)|accessdate=2018-05-15}}</ref> In March 2010, [[Derby News Network]] claimed that more than 98% of roller derby competitions were conducted under WFTDA rules.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derbynewsnetwork.com/2010/03/dnn_releases_first_power_rankings_2010|title=DNN Releases First Power Rankings of 2010|publisher=Derby News Network|date=2010-03-05|accessdate=2011-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111201041743/http://www.derbynewsnetwork.com/2010/03/dnn_releases_first_power_rankings_2010|archive-date=2011-12-01|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> For example, members of the [[United Kingdom Roller Derby Association]] are required to play by WFTDA rules,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ukrda.org.uk/?page_id=12|title=Join Us|publisher=United Kingdom Roller Derby Association|accessdate=2011-10-04}}</ref> while members of the former Canadian Women's Roller Derby Association were encouraged to join the WFTDA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwrda.ca/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510105027/http://www.cwrda.ca/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=2009-05-10|title=Welcome to CWRDA|publisher=Canadian Women's Roller Derby Association|accessdate=2011-10-05}}</ref>
===Basics of play=== {| class="wikitable" style="float: right; width: 45%; margin-left: 0.5em" |- !style="background: #efefef;"|Position !style="background: #efefef;"|Helmet cover<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|7}} !style="background: #efefef;"|Responsibility |- |Jammer |Stars |Scores points by lapping opposing team members, which can include a point attained by passing the opposing team's jammer<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|7}} |- |Blocker |None |Forms the pack,<ref name="parnavelas" />{{rp|18}} hinders the opposing jammer from passing through the pack, and helps their team's jammer pass through the pack.<ref>{{cite web|title=Derby 101|url=http://canberrarollerderbyleague.com/?page_id=154|publisher=Canberra Roller Derby League|accessdate=25 July 2012}}</ref> |- |Pivot |Stripe |A blocker who may be converted to a jammer during the course of a jam,<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|7}} if the jammer's helmet cover is correctly transferred in a "star pass" maneuver.<ref name="parnavelas" />{{rp|29}} The pivot is often an experienced player who establishes team strategy during play and sets the pace of the pack.<ref name="LearnPivot">{{cite web|url=http://www.derbylife.com/2016/04/learning-to-pivot-in-roller-derby/|title=Learning to Pivot in Roller Derby|publisher=DerbyLife.com|author=Em Dash|date=2016-04-22|accessdate=2018-05-16}}</ref><ref name="parnavelas" />{{rp|19}} |} Roller derby is played in two periods of 30 minutes.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|4}} Two teams of up to 15 players each field up to five members for episodes called "jams." Jams last two minutes unless called off prematurely.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|5}} Each team designates a scoring player (the "jammer"); the other four members are "blockers." One blocker can be designated as a "pivot"—a blocker who is allowed to become a jammer in the course of play.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|7}} The next jam may involve different players of the 15 roster players, and different selections for jammer and pivot.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|7}}
During each jam, players skate counterclockwise on a circuit track. Points are scored only by a team's jammer. After breaking through the pack and skating one lap to begin another "trip" through the pack, the jammer scores one point for passing any member of the opposing team.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|33}} The rules describe an "earned" pass; notably, the jammer must be in-bounds and upright. The jammer's first earned pass scores a point for passing that opponent and a point for each opponent not on the track (for instance, serving a penalty, or when the opposition did not field five players for the jam). If the jammer passes the entire pack and the opposing jammer too, it is a five-point scoring trip, commonly called a "grand slam."
Each team's blockers use body contact, changing positions, and other tactics to help their jammer score while hindering the opposing team's jammer.
===Jams=== [[File:TwoNorthWestJammers.jpg|thumb|left|Two jammers (from the [[Oly Rollers]] and [[Rainy City Roller Dolls|Rainy City]]) race from the jammer line]] Play begins by blockers lining up on the track anywhere between the "jammer line" and the "pivot line" 30 feet in front. The jammers start behind the jammer line.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|12}} Jams begin on a single short whistle blast, upon which both jammers and blockers may begin engaging immediately.
[[File:Texas Roller Derby Lonestar Rollergirls.jpg|thumb|Lonestar Rollergirls in Austin, Texas, play on a banked track. The jammer (wearing the starred helmet cover) is trying to pass a pivot (wearing a striped cover) with various blockers assisting.]] The pack is the largest single group of blockers containing members of both teams skating in proximity, arranged such that each player is within 10 feet of the next.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|11}} Blockers must maintain the pack, but can skate freely within 20 feet behind and ahead of it, an area known as the "engagement zone."<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|13}}
The first jammer to break through the pack earns the status of "lead jammer."<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|7}} A designated referee blows the whistle twice, and skates near, and points at, the lead jammer. Once earned, lead jammer status cannot be transferred to other skaters, but certain actions (notably, being sent to the penalty box) can cause it to be lost.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|8}} The lead jammer can stop the jam at any time by repeatedly placing both hands on their hips.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|}} If the jam is not stopped early, it ends after two minutes.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|5}} If time remains in the period, teams then have 30 seconds to get on the track and line up for the next jam.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|5}} If the period expires, it does not halt a jam that is underway.
===Blocking=== [[File:BlockerOnPivot.ogv|thumb|An Idahoan blocker impedes a Utahn pivot at Spudtown Knockdown IV in 2013 in [[Garden City, Idaho]].]] A skater may block an opponent to impede their movement or to force them out of bounds. The blocker must be upright, skating counterclockwise, in bounds, and within the engagement zone. Blocking with hands, elbows, head, and feet is prohibited, as is contact above the shoulders or below mid-thigh, and blocking from behind.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|14}}
===Penalties=== [[File:Roller derby, Amsterdam Derby Dames against the Ruhr Pott Roller Girls from Essen, Germany.jpg|thumb|220px|left|A German pivot attempts to knock a Dutch jammer out of bounds (the yellow line) at a 2011 bout held in [[Essen, Germany]].]] Referees penalize rules violations.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}} A player receiving a penalty is removed from play to sit in a [[penalty box]] for 30 seconds of jam time.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|29}} If the jam ends during this interval, the player remains in the penalty box during the subsequent jam until the interval ends.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|30}} The penalized player's team plays short-handed, as in [[ice hockey]].
However, the "power jam", derived from hockey's [[Power play (sporting term)#Ice hockey|"power play"]], does not cover any short-handed situation but only the case where the jammer is penalized.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://svrollergirls.wordpress.com/roller-derby-a-glossary/|title=Roller derby: A glossary|publisher=Silicon Valley Roller Girls|accessdate=2018-06-26}}</ref> In this case, that team cannot score. While the lead jammer is penalized, no one can prematurely end the jam.
It would be pointless to play if neither team could score; thus, a jammer is released from the penalty box early if the opponents' jammer enters the box. The second jammer's penalty is then only as long as the amount of time the first jammer spent in the box.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|31}} A player "fouls out" of the game on the seventh penalty, and is required to return to the locker room.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|32}}
===Equipment=== Players skate on four-wheeled ("quad") roller skates,<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|11}} and are required to wear protective equipment, including a helmet, wrist guards, elbow pads, knee pads, and mouth guards. All current sets of roller derby rules explicitly forbid [[inline skates]] for players. (USARS requires quad skates for all skaters. WFTDA and MRDA permit inline skates for referees, but virtually all referees wear quad skates.) Individual teams may mandate additional gear, such as padded knee length pants, similar to what aggressive skateboarders wear, and biologically specific gear such as a hard-case sports bra for female players and protective cups for males.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|39}}
==Strategy and tactics== Offense and defense are played simultaneously,<ref>{{Cite news |title=A Local Roller Derby Team Shows Its Toughness at a Saturday Bout but Doesn't Get a Win |author=Brauns, Katie |newspaper=Bend Bulletin |date=2009-04-14 |accessdate=2011-12-12 |url=http://www.bendbulletin.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20090412%2FSPORTS05%2F904120421%2F1041&nav}}</ref> a volatile aspect that complicates strategy and tactics. For example, blockers may create a large hole for their jammer to pass through and score, but this same maneuver might also allow the opposing team's jammer to score.<ref name="vodoo1">{{cite web|last=Vodoo|first=Big Daddy|title=Roller Derby Strategies and Plays|url=http://bigarmy.net/index.php?topic=74.0|publisher=Little City Roller Girs}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Joulwan|first=Melissa|title=Rollergirl: Totally True Tales from the Track - p 94|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wGizDBbRfjYC&pg=PA95 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |isbn=9781416538554|date=2007-04-06}}</ref>
[[Strategy|Strategies]] (high-level plans toward achieving the game's goal, which is to outscore the opposition) include the following: *'''Ending the jam''': The lead jammer can "call off" or end the jam at any time, controlling the opposition's ability to score points. The strategy for a jam is not to score a lot of points but to outscore the opposition. Often, the lead jammer scores as many points as possible on the first scoring trip, and then ends the jam before the opposing jammer can begin a scoring trip.<ref>{{cite web|title=Game Play: Strategy|url=http://www.atlantarollergirls.com/site_admin/about/the-game/strategy|publisher=Atlanta Roller Girls|accessdate=22 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928095235/http://www.atlantarollergirls.com/site_admin/about/the-game/strategy|archive-date=28 September 2011|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> If the jammer gets the lead but falls behind the opposing jammer, the coach may conclude that the team will be outscored and direct the jammer to call off the jam. *'''Passing the star''': The jammer for a team may "pass the star" (may perform a "star pass") to the pivot—that is, hand the helmet cover with the star to the pivot, which turns the pivot into the jammer.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|9}} Passing the star does not nullify any earned pass of an opponent that the former jammer made, but passing the star forward never constitutes an earned pass. A jammer might pass the star because of fatigue, injury, or because the pivot is in a better position to score.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fivepointgrandslam.blogspot.com/2011/07/by-position-pivotno-1.html|title=Five Point Grand Slam: By the Position – Pivot/No. 1|first=Tripp|last=Crouse|date=15 July 2011|website=Fivepointgrandslam.blogspot.com|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> Passing the star is also sometimes referred to as "passing the panty", as helmet covers are sometimes known as "panties".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://derbystein.wordpress.com/2015/08/09/passing-the-panty/|title=Passing the Panty|date=9 August 2015|website=Derbystein.wordpress.com|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref> *'''Penalty-killing''': Captained by the pivot, blockers adapt their play to a penalty situation. For example, a short-handed team may try to make the pack skate faster to slow down scoring action until the team returns to full strength.<ref name="LearnPivot" />
[[Tactic (method)|Tactics]] (deliberate conceptual tasks in support of the strategy) may include the following: *'''Walling up''': Two or more blockers skate together to make it difficult for the opposing team (especially its jammer) to maneuver. They may skate side-by-side and use a "wide stance" to maximize the blockade, but must not link with or grasp each other, or otherwise form an impenetrable connection.<ref name="WFTDARules" /> The ability to suddenly form a wall denies the opposition time to respond. A wall can inhibit, slow down, and ultimately trap the opposing jammer. An effective wall may last for an entire jam. Variations on the tactic include the following: **Backwards bracing, in which one skater, forward of the wall, skates backward to sight the jammer and direct teammates forming the wall. **A skater may break off from the wall to actively challenge the opposing jammer, with a teammate replacing the skater in the wall.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bump|first=Speed|title=Strategy 101: The Wall|url=https://www.rosecityrollers.com/strategy-101-the-wall/|publisher=Rose City Rollers|accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref> **If the opposing jammer tries to pass the wall on one side, players may abandon the other side to fortify the active side of the wall. [[File:Roller Derby (22).jpg|thumb|right|Two [[Richter City Roller Derby|Wellington]] skaters (in purple) form a wall, limiting their opponents' movement, while their jammer (leftmost skater in purple) takes a hip whip to accelerate past the pack]] *'''Jammer tactics''', in response to a wall or other obstacles by the defense, include the following: **Pushing through gaps in the wall or inducing the wall to separate by use of physical force. **Evading the obstacle to one side or the other. **[[Juke (football move)|Juking]], where the jammer seems to be skating to one side but quickly shifts to the other side. **Rolling around the end of the obstacle (spinning 360°) to end up forward of it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pivotstar.com/evasive-jamming-pt1/|title=Roller Derby Training: Evasive Jamming – Part One|author=Lucy Croysdill|publisher=pivotstar.com|accessdate=2018-09-29}}</ref> **Using teammates to impede the defense from adjusting, such as by setting [[Screen (sports)|screens]]. **Using a '''whip''', where one or more teammates grasp the jammer's hand(s) and swing the jammer forward, transferring speed and momentum to the jammer.<ref>{{cite book|last=Joulwan|first=Melissa|title=Rollergirl: Totally True Tales from the Track - p 95|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wGizDBbRfjYC&pg=PA95 |publisher=Simon and Schuster |isbn=9781416538554|date=2007-04-06}}</ref> **Using the inside curve of the track to leap out of bounds but land in bounds. *'''Goating''': The pack is defined as ''the largest group of in-bounds blockers, skating in proximity, containing members from both teams.''<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|11}} In the "goat-herding" tactic, one team surrounds a blocker of the opposing team, and then slows so that that group becomes the pack. The rest of the opposing team, skating ahead, are thus put out of play and cannot legally block the goat-herders' jammer. *'''Running back''' or '''recycling''': When a skater bumps the opponent jammer off the track, the jammer can only re-enter the track behind the skater. The skater skates clockwise on the track toward the rear of the engagement zone to maximize the time the jammer must spend before returning to action.<ref name=western-style>{{cite news| url = http://www.chicagoreader.com/chicago/western-style-roller-derby-windy-city-rollers/Content?oid=2592374| title = Game Changer| work = [[Chicago Reader]]| date = 21 October 2010| first = Ling |last = Ma| accessdate = 31 October 2010}}</ref> *'''Bridging''': By separating up to 10 feet, blockers can stretch both the pack and the engagement zone, allowing teammates to keep hindering the opposition jammer. For example, in the strategy of running back (see above), coordinated action by the four skaters other than the jammer could force the opponent jammer to detour a full 40 feet before returning to action.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Falcon|first1=M|title=Derby Techniques of Interest Part 1: Knocking a jammer out of bounds and forming a bridge|url=http://www.tbayrollergirls.com/derby-techniques-of-interest/|publisher=Thunder Bay Roller Derby League|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref>
==Officials== WFTDA bouts are officiated by three to seven skating referees<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|35}} and many non-skating officials (NSOs). Referees skate on the inside of the track; in flat-track derby, some also skate on the outside of the track. They call penalties, award points, and ensure safe game play.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}} Referees must wear skates and typically wear white and black stripes.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|38}} NSOs take up a range of positions inside and outside the track, start and time the jams, record and display scores and penalties communicated by referees, record the number of each skater on track for a given jam, and time and record skaters in the penalty box. Volunteer leagues adapt when fewer than the optimal number of officials are present.
===Referees===
{| class="wikitable" |- !style="background: #efefef;"|Type !style="background: #efefef;"|Number !style="background: #efefef;"|Responsibility |- |'''Head Referee''' |1 |The head referee is responsible for the general supervision of the bout and has final authority on all rulings. The head referee skates as an inside pack referee, but is also responsible for issuing expulsions<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|35}} and for announcing the results of official reviews.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|38}} |- |'''Pack Referee''' |Up to 5 |Pack referees are responsible for watching the skaters in the pack, pack definition and calling penalties. They are located both inside and outside the track.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|35}}<ref name="parnavelas">{{cite book |last=Parnavelas |first=Ellen |title=The Roller Derby Athlete |year= 2012 |publisher=[[Bloomsbury Publishing|Bloomsbury]] |location=London |isbn=978-1-4088-3239-4}}</ref>{{rp|29}} |- |'''Jammer Referees''' |2 |Skating on the inside of the track,<ref name="parnavelas" />{{rp|29}} jammer referees watch the jammers of a specific team and wear a wristband (and optionally a helmet cover) in that team's color to identify which team they are watching.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|35}} They award points for opponents passed by their jammer,<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}} and signal whether theirs is the lead jammer.<ref name="parnavelas" />{{rp|29}} |}
===Non-skating officials (NSOs)===
{| class="wikitable" |- !style="background: #efefef;"|Type !style="background: #efefef;"|Number !style="background: #efefef;"|Responsibility |- |'''Scorekeepers''' |2 |Record points scored by jammers.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}} |- |'''Penalty Trackers''' |1 (min) |Trackers record each skater's penalties<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}} and notify the head referee of skaters in the current jam who are in danger of fouling out.<ref name="WFTDARules" /> |- |'''Penalty Box Manager''' |1 |The manager is the head of the affairs within the penalty box. The manager can call penalties for penalty box violations or illegal procedures (such as removing the helmet in the penalty box). Also, the manager points where the player is assigned to sit, times the jammers, and executes any necessary jammer swap.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}} |- |'''Penalty Box Timers''' |2 (min) |Penalty box timers ensure skaters sent to the penalty box serve their entire penalties,<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}} and notify referees if any do not.<ref name="WFTDARules" /> |- |'''Jam Timer''' |1 |The jam timer starts jams, signals when a jam runs to the full two minutes, times the 30 seconds between jams,<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}} and calls an official timeout if the teams are not ready to start a new jam at the end of that interval. |- |'''Inside Whiteboard''' |1 |This NSO maintains a whiteboard in the center of the track that shows each skater's accumulated penalties.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}} |- |'''Lineup''' |2 |This NSO records every player on the track in each jam<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|5}} |- |'''Scoreboard Operator''' |1 |This NSO updates each team's score after every scoring pass.<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|36}}<ref name="WFTDARules" /> |}
==History==
===Professional endurance races=== {{Main article|History of roller derby}}<!--This SUMMARY is pulled from the History of roller derby article.--> [[File:Roller Derby 1950.jpg|left|thumb|Two women's league roller derby skaters leap over two who have fallen in a March 1950 bout in [[New York City]]]] The growing popularity of [[roller skating]] in the United States led to the formation of organized multi-day endurance races for cash prizes, as early as the mid-1880s.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Remarkable roller-skating feat|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=1884-04-13|page=10}}</ref><ref name=chicago-tribune>{{Cite news|title=A six-day roller skate race|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=1885-03-02|page=10}}</ref><ref name=NYT-1885>{{Cite news|title=On rollers for six days: beginning the race at the Madison-Square Garden. Thirty-six entries, including Frank Hart and several champions—cheering the start|newspaper=New York Times|date=2 March 1885|page=10}}</ref> Speed and endurance races continued to be held on both flat and banked tracks in the century's first three decades<ref name=Chicagi-Daily-1908>{{Cite news|title=Roller marathon thrills and jars: 100 boys meet with adventures and tumbles in West Side Boulevard race. Dodge cars and autos. But records are smashed by contestants in red tights, overalls, etc|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=1908-11-27|page=5}}</ref> and spectators enjoyed the spills and falls of the skaters.<ref name=NYT-52-1914>{{Cite news|title=Roller skating on banked track: old-time sport is revived with speed contests at the Garden|newspaper=New York Times|date=1922-12-17|page=11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=24-hour roller race: Ollie Moore will be teamed with Willie Blackburn at Garden|newspaper=New York Times|date=1914-12-17|page=S2}}</ref> The term ''derby'' was used to refer to such races by 1922.<ref name=CDT-4-24>{{Cite news|title=Roller derby on tomorrow|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=1922-04-24|page=20}}</ref>{{#tag:ref | "Roland Cloni of Akron, world's champion roller skater, who yesterday tried out the track in the Broadway armory, where the national roller skating derby will be held this week, asserted new world's records can be established for flat tracks. The derby will open tomorrow and run until Saturday."<ref name="CDT-4-24" />|group="note"}}
===Evolution to contact sport=== The endurance races began to transform into the contemporary form of the sport in the mid-1930s, when promoter [[Leo Seltzer]]{{#tag:ref | Sources disagree on whether it was Leo alone or with his brother, the skate maker Oscar Seltzer.<ref name=SF-book-79>{{Cite book|title=San Francisco Bizarro: A Guide to Notorious Sights, Lusty Pursuits, and Downright Freakiness in the City by the Bay|last=Boulware|first=Jack|year=2000|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=0-312-20671-2|page=79}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.metroactive.com/papers/cruz/07.24.97/rollerqueen-9730.html|title=Blood on the Tracks|last=Luker|first=Kelly|date=1997-07-23|accessdate=2008-07-13|newspaper=Metro Santa Cruz}}</ref>|group="note"}}{{#tag:ref | "Roller derby has entertained the masses in one form or another since the 1930s, when brothers Leo and Oscar Seltzer conceptualized the idea of a skating contest on a Chicago restaurant tablecloth."<ref name="SF-book-79" />|group="note"}} created the Transcontinental Roller Derby, a month-long simulation of a road race between two-person teams of professional skaters.<ref name="rasmussen">{{Cite news|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|last=Rasmussen|first=Cecilia|date=1999-02-21|title=L.A. Then and Now: The Man Who Got Roller Derby Rolling Along}}</ref> The spectacle became a popular touring exhibition.<ref name="time_feb1936">{{Cite news|magazine=Time|title=Roller Derby|date=1936-02-03|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,755740-1,00.html|accessdate=2008-07-13}}</ref><ref name="time_variations">{{Cite news|magazine=Time|date=1936-09-21|title=Variations|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,756673,00.html|accessdate=2008-07-13}}</ref> In the late 1930s, sportswriter [[Damon Runyon]] persuaded Seltzer to change the Roller Derby rules to increase skater contact.<ref name="rasmussen" /> By 1939, after experimenting with different team and scoring arrangements, Seltzer's created a touring company of four pairs of teams (always billed as the local "home" team versus either New York or Chicago),<ref name="deford_84">{{Cite book |title=Five Strides on the Banked Track: The life and times of the Roller Derby|last=Deford|first=Frank|year=1971|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|page=84|isbn=0-316-17920-5}}</ref> with two five-person teams on the track at once, scoring points when its members lapped opponents.<ref name="NMRS_2004">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollerskatingmuseum.com/derby.htm |title=Roller Derby at the National Museum of Roller Skating |year=2004 |accessdate=2007-06-08 |publisher=National Roller Skating Museum |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070222193457/http://www.rollerskatingmuseum.com/derby.htm |archivedate=2007-02-22 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
===Television=== On November 29, 1948, before television viewership was widespread, ''Roller Derby'' debuted on New York [[television]].<ref name=dedford />{{rp|89}} The broadcasts increased spectator turnout for live matches.<ref name="rushin">{{Cite news |url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1014779/index.htm |title=A Forward Roll: Dusted off and spiffed up, the Roller Derby is aiming to regain the hold it once had on TV |date=1998-12-14 |periodical=Sports Illustrated |last1=Rushin |first1=Steve |author-link=Steve Rushin |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908040817/http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1014779/index.htm |archive-date=2008-09-08 |accessdate=2018-04-24 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> For the 1949–1950 season, Seltzer formed the [[National Roller Derby League]] (NRDL), comprising six teams.<ref name="KTVU">{{cite web |url=http://www.ktvu.com/station/1854338/detail.html |title=Roller Derby |publisher=KTVU-TV |year=2004 |accessdate=2007-06-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405093016/http://www.ktvu.com/station/1854338/detail.html |archivedate= 2007-04-05 |df= }}</ref><ref name=dedford />{{rp|95}} NRDL season playoffs sold out Madison Square Garden for a week.<ref name="KTVU" /> During the late 1950s and 1960s, the sport was broadcast on several networks, but attendance declined. [[Jerry Seltzer]] (Leo's son), the ''Roller Derby'' "commissioner", hoped to use television to expand the live spectator base. He adapted the sport for television by developing scripted story lines and rules designed to improve television appeal, but derby's popularity declined.<ref name=dedford>{{cite book|last=Deford|first=Frank|title=Five Strides on the Banked Track: The Life and Times of the Roller Derby|publisher=Little, Brown and Company|year=1971|isbn=0-316-17920-5}}</ref>
1989 saw the debut of ''[[RollerGames]],'' an even more theatrical variant of roller derby for national audiences. It used a figure-8 track and rules adapted for this track. Bill Griffiths, Sr. served as commissioner while his son, Bill Griffiths, Jr., managed the L.A. T-Birds, who (according to the storyline) were seeking revenge on the Violators (led by Skull) for cheating in the Commissioner's Cup. The other teams included the Maniacs (led by Guru Drew), Bad Attitude (led by Ms. Georgia Hase), the Rockers (led by DJ Terringo and consisting of skaters who were also professional rock and roll musicians), and Hot Flash (led by Juan Valdez Lopez). It ran one season, because some of its syndicators went bankrupt.
In 1999, [[The Nashville Network|TNN]] (now [[Spike TV]]) debuted ''[[RollerJam]],'' which used the classic rules and banked oval track, but allowed inline skates (although some skaters wore traditional quad skates). Jerry Seltzer was commissioner for this version.
==Contemporary roller derby==
[[File:Roller derby track.svg|center|thumb|500px| Standard (WFTDA/MRDA/USARS<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://usars.info/rules/derby/2015/2015RollerDerbyRuleBook_FullVersion.pdf|title=USARS Rules of Roller Derby|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> flat track roller derby) track. The MADE track differs in that the straightaways do not taper but are uniform in width along their full length.]]
===Amateur revival=== [[File:Attacker (2222615188).jpg|right|thumb|A Windy City Rollers (Chicago, Illinois) jammer]]
[[File:NewZealandRollerDerby2010-11-27.jpg|thumb|Teams competing in [[Hobart]], [[Australia]], in November 2010]] Roller derby began its modern revival in [[Austin, Texas]] in the early 2000s as an all-female, woman-organized amateur sport.<ref name="ddan">{{cite journal|journal=New York Times|title=Pushing the Limit: The Dude of Roller Derby and His vision|last=Brick|first=Michael|date=2008-12-17|accessdate=2008-12-17|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/12/18/sports/othersports/18devildan.html?_r=2&pagewanted=all}}</ref> By August 2006, there were over 135 similar leagues.<ref name="nyt200811">{{cite journal|journal=New York Times|title=With Names That Could Kill, Women Rev Up Roller Derby|last=La Gorce|first=Tammy|date=2008-11-07|accessdate=2008-12-17|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/09/nyregion/new-jersey/09rollernj.html}} (New York print edition: 2008-11-09 p. NJ6)</ref> Leagues outside the U.S. also began forming in 2006, and international competition soon followed. There are over 2,000 amateur leagues worldwide<ref name="flattrackstats">{{cite web|url=http://flattrackstats.com/teams|title=Teams - Roller Derby Stats & Rankings - Flat Track Stats|website=flattrackstats.com|accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref> in countries including [[Canada]], [[Australia]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[France]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kgpbPuVdVEo |title=Paris, les filles et le Roller Derby (Paris Roller Girls) |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2012-04-08 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref> [[Brazil]], [[New Zealand]], [[Germany]], [[Belgium]], [[Finland]], [[Norway]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oslorollerderby.no/|title=Oslo Roller Derby|accessdate=2013-01-30}}</ref> [[Sweden]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derbyroster.com/|title=Roller Derby Worldwide|accessdate=2011-09-08|author=Cat O'Ninetails|year=2011}}</ref> [[Denmark]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.copenhagenrollerderby.com/|title=Copenhagen Roller Derby|website=Copenhagenrollerderby.com|accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref> [[Israel]],<ref>[http://tlvderbygirls.com/about-he/tlvderbygirls-he/ TLV Derby Girls] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714124806/http://tlvderbygirls.com/about-he/tlvderbygirls-he/ |date=2014-07-14 }}. Official site</ref> [[Singapore]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thechillipadis.wordpress.com/|title=Roller Derby Singapore|website=Roller Derby Singapore|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest+News/Sports/Story/A1Story20111219-316951.html|title=New roller derby sport kicks off in Singapore|publisher=asiaone.com|date=2011-12-19|accessdate=2012-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cprKMZhL82M |title=Roller Derby Singapore &#124; CPDG &#124; Teaser Video |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2011-04-01 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref> [[Dubai]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Dani |url=http://www.dubairollerderby.com/1/post/2012/10/in-the-beginning.html |title=In the beginning |publisher=Dubai Roller Derby |date=2012-10-13 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeoutdubai.com/sportandoutdoor/features/38264-21-sports-in-dubai-this-week#.UPxsU325du0 |title=21 sports in Dubai this week - Sport & Outdoor Features |website=TimeOutDubai.com |date=2013-01-15 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref> and [[Egypt]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derbylife.com/articles/2012/11/close_and_personal_cairollers_cairo_egypt |title=Up Close and Personal with the CaiRollers of Cairo, Egypt |website=DerbyLife.com |date= |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jezebel.com/5963517/egypts-cairollers-have-best-name-ever-are-super-rad-rollergirls |title=Egypt's Cairollers Have Best Name Ever, Are Super Rad Rollergirls |website=Jezebel.com |date=2012-11-27 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rollerderbyjesus.com/2013/01/18/thoughts-on-the-start-of-the-12th-year-of-modern-roller-derby/ |title=thoughts on the start of the 12th year of Modern Roller Derby « Jerry Seltzer |website=Rollerderbyjesus.com |date=2013-01-18 |accessdate=2013-02-15}}</ref> In many international leagues, gear and equipment must be imported.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynewsegypt.com/2013/03/13/cairollers-bring-roller-derby-to-egypt/|title=Cairollers Bring Roller Derby to Egypt|website=Dailynewsegypt.com}}</ref> Roller derby's contemporary resurgence has been regarded as an aspect of [[globalization]] which demonstrates "the speed with which [[popular culture|pop culture]] is now transported by highly mobile [[expatriate]]s and [[social media]], while also highlighting the changing role of women in many societies."<ref name="autogenerated1"/>
Many roller derby leagues are amateur, self-organized and all-female<ref>{{cite web|last=Whittaker |first=Richard |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/gyrobase/Issue/story?oid=oid:921441 |title=Electric Skaterland: Austin births a Roller Derby revolution Austin Sports |website=AustinChronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2010-08-31}}</ref> and were formed in a do-it-yourself spirit by relatively new enthusiasts.<ref>{{cite video |date=2008-02-22 |title=The Dames: The Story of the Boston Roller Derby League|url=http://www.cctvcambridge.org/node/2495/play |format=QuickTime |medium= |publisher=Cambridge Community Television|location=Cambridge, MA |accessdate=2008-06-23 |time=26:50}} See also the [http://www.cctvcambridge.org/thedames accompanying blog post].</ref> In many leagues (especially in the U.S.), a [[punk subculture|punk]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2005/may/23/ussport.stevenwells|author=|accessdate=|title=Roller derby gets a good punking |date=2005-05-23 |location=London |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |first=Steven|last=Wells}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourstage.com/blog/2009/11/13/punk-on-the-rocks-roller-derby-wreckers|author=|accessdate=|title=Punk On The Rocks: Roller Derby Wrecker|date=|website=Ourstage.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331220535/http://www.ourstage.com/blog/2009/11/13/punk-on-the-rocks-roller-derby-wreckers|archive-date=2012-03-31|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> [[aesthetics|aesthetic]] and/or [[third-wave feminism|third-wave feminist]]<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://youngerwomenstaskforce.blogspot.com/2006/10/roller-derby-uniting-younger-women-one.html|title= Roller Derby: Uniting Younger Women, One Bout at a Time|date=2006-10-26 |accessdate=2008-06-18 |author="Jackie"|publisher=Younger Women's Task Force}} (This is a post on the main YWTF blog.)</ref> [[ethic]] is prominent.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uncleboise.com/feature.boi?a=167 |title=Oddballs: Roller Derby |author=Pat Zanghi |publisher=Uncle Boise |date=2010-04-22 |accessdate=2009-05-25 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528174435/http://uncleboise.com/feature.boi?a=167 |archivedate=2010-05-28}}</ref> Members of fledgling leagues often practice and strategize together, regardless of team affiliation, between bouts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Soldiers in the Roller Derby|url=http://armylive.dodlive.mil/index.php/2009/06/soldiers-in-the-roller-derby/|publisher=Army Live}}</ref> Most compete on flat tracks, though several leagues skate on banked tracks, with more in the planning stages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.renorollergirls.com/ |title=Reno Roller Girls |publisher=Reno Roller Girls |date= |accessdate=2010-08-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110202200406/http://renorollergirls.com/ |archive-date=2011-02-02 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
Each league typically features local teams in public bouts that are popular with a diverse fan base.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wftda.com/sponsors/2011-demographic-information |title=WFTDA 2011 Demographic Survey Results |publisher=WFTDA |accessdate=2011-03-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402145943/http://wftda.com/sponsors/2011-demographic-information |archivedate=2011-04-02}} </ref> Some venues host audiences ranging up to 7,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videos.nj.com/star-ledger/2011/04/new_jersey_roller_derby_packs.html|title=New Jersey Roller Derby packs thousands into Convention Hall - Video - NJ.com<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Videos.nj.com|accessdate=2017-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307185711/http://videos.nj.com/star-ledger/2011/04/new_jersey_roller_derby_packs.html|archive-date=2016-03-07|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Successful local leagues have formed [[traveling team]]s comprising the league's best players to compete with comparable teams from other cities and regions. In February 2012, the [[International Olympic Committee]] considered roller derby, among eight sports, for inclusion in the 2020 Olympic Games.<ref>{{cite web|last=Van |first=Samantha |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/top/news?slug=ycn-10930615 |title=Roller Derby May Be Included in 2020 Olympics: A Female's Reaction|website=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-06}}</ref><ref> {{cite news| url=http://www.cnn.com/video/?%2Fvideo%2Fsports%2F2012%2F05%2F11%2Fnr-baldwin-roller-derby.cnn#/video/sports/2012/05/11/nr-baldwin-roller-derby.cnn | work=CNN | title=CNN.com Video}}</ref>
In 2009, the [[feature film]] ''[[Whip It (film)|Whip It]]'' was based on roller derby and introduced viewers to its rules and culture. The WFTDA encouraged leagues to coordinate with promotions during the film's release to increase awareness of the leagues.<ref>{{cite web|last=Loca|first=Chica|title=Whip It-Marketing Session|url=http://wftda.com/wftda-whip-it-marketing-rollercon2009.pdf|publisher=WFTDA|accessdate=24 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120820052255/http://wftda.com/wftda-whip-it-marketing-rollercon2009.pdf|archive-date=20 August 2012|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Corporate advertising has used roller derby themes in television commercials for [[insurance]],<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/embed/9xPFC5qkJ1k | title = Shannon and Heather's aha moment commercial - YouTube | website = www.YouTube.com | accessdate = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> a [[breakfast cereal]],<ref>{{YouTube|zDxFHNF8kTg|Cheerios TV ad}}</ref> and an [[over-the-counter]] [[analgesic]].<ref>{{YouTube|bm8BTcL-MQI|Aleve TV ad}}</ref>
===Derby names=== [[File:2011-04-03 DustDevil (FoCo v Pacific)-1005.jpg|left|thumb|Santa Cruz Derby Girls v Pacific Roller Derby at the 2011 Dust Devil tournament. Players wear a uniform shirt with leggings. Some wear short shorts and knee/thigh high socks.]]
{| style="margin-left:0.5em; XXXpadding-left:22px; float:right;" class="wikitable" |+ Examples of derby names<ref name=twoevils1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.twoevils.org/rollergirls/|title=International Rollergirls' Master Roster|author=King, April, ed.|publisher=twoevils.org|date=2014-09-01|accessdate=2018-06-17}}</ref> ! Name!! Allusion |- | Guinefear of Jamalot || [[Guinevere]] of Camelot |- | Mazel Tov Cocktail || [[Mazel tov]], [[Molotov cocktail]] |- | O Hell No Kitty || [[Hello Kitty]] |- | Sandra Day O'Clobber || [[Sandra Day O'Connor]] |- | Punky Bruiser || [[Punky Brewster]] |- | Roly Mary Mother of Quad|| Holy Mary Mother of God |- | Ania Marx || On Your Marks |- | Princess Lay-Ya Flat || [[Princess Leia]] |- | Anna Mosity || [[wikt:animosity|Animosity]] |- | Smack Ops || Black Ops |- | Trauma Queen|| Drama Queen |}
Most players in roller leagues skate under pseudonyms, also called "[[derby name]]s" or "skater names." These typically use [[word play]] with satirical, mock-violent or sexual [[pun]]s, [[alliteration]], and allusions to [[popular culture|pop culture]]. [[Referees#Roller derby|Referees]] use derby names as well,<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.derbynewsnetwork.com/blogs/justice_feelgood_marshall/2008/12/killbox_retires_sort|title=Killbox retires (sort of)|publisher=[[Derby News Network]]|author=Tracy "Justice Feelgood Marshall" Williams|date=2008-12-08|accessdate=2008-12-30|journal=&mdash;|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101225211439/http://derbynewsnetwork.com/blogs/justice_feelgood_marshall/2008/12/killbox_retires_sort|archive-date=2010-12-25|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> often shown on the backs of their striped uniforms. Some players claim their names represent [[alter ego]]s that they adopt while skating.<ref name="derby brats">{{cite web|url=http://www.seattleschild.com/article/seattle-derby-brats-no-flash-in-the-pan1|title=Seattle Derby Brats – No Flash in the Pan|accessdate=2010-08-23|quote=It's like your alter ego," Grianne says, "You don't want to be announced as Grianne Hunter. You want to be something tougher.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110124005030/http://www.seattleschild.com/article/seattle-derby-brats-no-flash-in-the-pan1|archive-date=2011-01-24|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
Whether a team should skate under real names or derby names is sometimes debated.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverrollerdolls.org/index.php/teams/mile-high-club/|title=Denver Roller Dolls—Teams—Mile High Club|accessdate=2009-07-19|quote=This season, 13 of the team's members are making the switch from derby names to real names.}}</ref> Some derby names are obscene, and this attracts controversy among other skaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derbylife.com/articles/2011/09/derby_names_not_ready_prime_time |title=Derby Names: Not Ready for Prime Time |website=DerbyLife.com |date=2011-09-14 |accessdate=2011-09-24}}</ref>
Copying of derby names has attracted legal and sociological analysis as an example of indigenous development of property rights.<ref name=Fagundes /> New players are encouraged to check derby names against an international roster to ensure they are not already in use.<ref name=twoevils1 /><ref>[https://derbyrollcall.com Derby Roll Call] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821140439/http://www.derbyrollcall.com/ |date=2018-08-21 }}.</ref>
The names of roller derby events are also sardonic and convoluted—for example, Night of the Rolling Dead ([[Night of the Living Dead]]), Knocktoberfest ([[Oktoberfest]]), Spanksgiving ([[Thanksgiving]]), Seasons Beatings ([[Christmas and holiday season|Seasons Greetings]]), Grandma Got Run Over By a Rollergirl ([[Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer]]), Cinco de May-hem ([[Cinco de Mayo]]), and War of the Wheels ([[The War of the Worlds|War of the Worlds]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.treasurevalleyrollergirls.net/news.html |title=Treasure Valley Rollergirls |publisher=Treasure Valley Rollergirls |date= |accessdate=2010-08-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724112536/http://www.treasurevalleyrollergirls.net/news.html |archive-date=2011-07-24 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref>
===Safety=== [[File:DerbySpiralFractureFIXED.JPG|thumb|[[Emergency medical technician|EMT]]s and others tend to an injured skater.]] Roller derby is a contact sport, and injuries can occur. Superficial injuries include torn eyelashes and "fishnet burn", a stippled effect of falling while wearing fishnet hose.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=How Roller Derby Works|publisher=HowStuffWorks, Inc.|last=Wilson|first=Tracy|url=http://entertainment.howstuffworks.com/roller-derby6.htm|accessdate=2008-06-22}}</ref> However, torn ligaments, broken bones, and [[concussion]]s also occur.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.nj.com/morristown/index.ssf/2008/11/anatomy_of_a_concussion.html | title = Anatomy of a concussion | website = NJ.com | access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url = http://blog.timesunion.com/rollerderby/dain-bramage/393/ | title = Dain Bramage | website = Roller Derby | language = en-US | access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rollerderbydisorder.blogspot.com/2008/06/pcl-injuries-in-roller-derby.html|title=PCL Injuries in Roller Derby|last=Ryder|first=Kari|accessdate=2008-06-22}}</ref>
Some leagues prominently display their injuries, to embellish the image of violence or [[machismo]].<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.ratcityrollergirls.com/injuries.html |title=Injury Gallery |publisher=Rat City Rollergirls |accessdate=2008-06-22 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026040642/http://www.ratcityrollergirls.com/injuries.html |archivedate=2007-10-26|deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.mnrollergirls.com/photos/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814113205/http://www.mnrollergirls.com/photos/index_SIMPLE.php?album=Pabst_Bruise_Gallery |archivedate=2007-08-14 |title=Pabst Bruise Gallery |publisher=Minnesota RollerGirls |accessdate=2008-06-22 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> However, some skaters say the sport is reasonably safe if skaters take precautions.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.skatelogforum.com/forums/showthread.php?t=5090 | title = Derby injuries? - SkateLog Forum | website = Skatelogforum.com | access-date = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> The rules require appropriate medical professionals on-site at every bout,<ref name="WFTDARules" />{{rp|39}} even if not required by laws or arena regulations. The WFTDA offers insurance for leagues in the United States with legal liability and accident coverage, but it recommends that skaters also carry their own primary medical insurance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wftda.org/resources/insurance|title=WFTDA Insurance Program|publisher=WFTDA|accessdate=2018-06-18}}</ref>
===Expansion=== Although the early 2000s revival of roller derby was initially all-female, some leagues later introduced all-male teams and unisex games; {{as of|2013|05|lc=yes}} there were over 140 [[junior roller derby]] programs in the United States, and many more around the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.derbyroster.com/index.php|title=Roller Derby Worldwide|access-date=2013-05-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130111173106/http://www.derbyroster.com/index.php|archive-date=2013-01-11|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
Roller derby bouts are now [[Streaming media|streamed]] online, and there is archived video of past bouts and tournaments. The WFTDA offers live streaming video of its tournaments at <code>wftda.tv</code>. [[Derby News Network]] (<code>www.DerbyNewsNetwork.com</code>) offered live streaming video and archived video including events outside the WFTDA.
FiveOnFive magazine covers roller derby and diverse aspects such as business, training, junior roller derby, and nutrition.<ref name="FiveOnFive Magazine">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiveonfivemag.com/|title=fiveonfive » women’s flat track roller derby magazine|website=Fiveonfivemag.com|accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref>
==Governance and organization== {{Main article|List of roller derby associations}} The largest governing body for the sport is the [[Women's Flat Track Derby Association]] (WFTDA), with 397 full member leagues and 48 apprentice leagues.<ref name="WFTDA Member Leagues">{{Cite web |title=WFTDA Leagues |publisher=WFTDA |date=2017 |accessdate=2017-07-08 |url=https://wftda.com/wftda-leagues/}}</ref> WFTDA membership is a major goal of aspiring leagues.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.sbnation.com/longform/2013/8/13/4614248/roller-derby-wftda-profile | title = The rise of roller derby | last = Dator | first = James | publisher = SBNation.com | accessdate = 2016-03-01 }}</ref> Other associations support either coed or men-only derby; the largest organization supporting male roller derby is the [[Men's Roller Derby Association]] (MRDA).<ref name=article1>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollerderbyinsidetrack.com/features/2011/the-state-of-derby-part-ii/|title=The State of Derby – Part II: OSDA and JRDA|access-date=2011-10-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110825054013/http://www.rollerderbyinsidetrack.com/features/2011/the-state-of-derby-part-ii/|archive-date=2011-08-25|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref><ref name=article2>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollerderbyinsidetrack.com/features/2011/the-state-of-derby-part-iii-modern-derby-athletic-endeavor/|title=The State of Derby – Part III: Modern Athletic Derby Endeavor|website=Rollerderbyinsidetrack.com|accessdate=2017-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905202747/http://www.rollerderbyinsidetrack.com/features/2011/the-state-of-derby-part-iii-modern-derby-athletic-endeavor/|archive-date=2011-09-05|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref><ref name=article3>{{cite web |url=http://www.rollerderbyinsidetrack.com/features/2011/the-state-of-derby-part-iv-mens-roller-derby-association/ |title=The State of Derby – Part IV: Men’s Roller Derby Association |author="Captain Gorgeous" |publisher=Roller Derby Inside Track |date=2011-06-28 |accessdate=2011-10-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110915071123/http://www.rollerderbyinsidetrack.com/features/2011/the-state-of-derby-part-iv-mens-roller-derby-association/ |archivedate=2011-09-15}} </ref> Within the United States, the Junior Roller Derby Association governs play by those under 18. It modifies the WFTDA rules for minors, such as prohibiting hitting and accelerating into a block.<ref name="Junior Roller Derby Association">{{cite web|url=http://www.juniorrollerderby.org/|title=HOME|website=Junior Roller Derby Association|accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref> Some U.S. leagues decline affiliation with a [[USA Roller Sports|national organization]] because they prefer local governance.<ref name=rejected>{{cite web|url=http://wftda.com/files/usars-reqest-for-endorsement.pdf|author=USA Roller Sports|title=To Whom It May Concern|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026094549/http://wftda.com/files/usars-reqest-for-endorsement.pdf |archivedate=2011-10-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://wftda.com/press/open-letter-to-usars|title=Open Letter to USA Roller Sports|publisher=Women's Flat Track Derby Association|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111010173737/http://wftda.com/press/open-letter-to-usars |archivedate=2011-10-10|accessdate=2012-02-04|date=2011-05-12}}</ref>
USA Roller Sports (USARS) is recognized by the International Roller Sports Federation (FIRS) and the United States Olympic Committee (USOC) as the National Governing Body of competitive roller sports in the United States, including speed, figure, hockey, roller derby and slalom. WFTDA and USARS maintain a reciprocity agreement for insurance purposes.<ref name=reciprocity-agreement>{{cite web |url=http://usarollersports.org/roller-derby/usars-wftda-reciprocity|accessdate=2011-10-12|publisher=USA Roller Sports |date=2009-06-24 |title=USARS / WFTDA Reciprocity |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006141048/http://usarollersports.org/roller-derby/usars-wftda-reciprocity|archivedate=2011-10-06}}</ref>
Outside the [[United States]], many roller derby leagues enjoy support from their national skate federations, such as [[Skate Australia]],<ref name=skate-australia>{{cite web |url=http://www.skateaustralia.org.au/index.php?option=com_content&view=section&layout=blog&id=7&Itemid=273 |title=Ballarat Junior Roller Derby Star Set for Battle |author=Rachel Afflick |accessdate=2011-10-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111007142434/http://www.skateaustralia.org.au/index.php?option=com_content&view=section&layout=blog&id=7&Itemid=273 |archivedate=2011-10-07}}</ref> the [[British Roller Sports Federation]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Roller Derby is now recognised as a sport in the UK, and UKRDA the National Association|url=http://www.euroderby.org/news/125-roller-derby-is-now-recognised-as-a-sport-in-the-uk-and-ukrda-the-national-association|website=Euroderby.org|accessdate=2011-10-02}}{{dead link|date=December 2017|bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}</ref> and [[Roller Sports Canada]].<ref name=skate-Canada>{{cite web|url=http://rollersports.ca/roller-derby/|title=Roller Derby|date=2010-01-07 |website=Rollersports.ca|accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref> In Europe, roller derby was recognized as a sport in Paris in 2010 by the Federation Internationale de Roller Sports (FIRS), which reports directly to the International Olympic Committee. As of 2017, FIRS has been accepted as the international rule set by the International Olympic Committee. Teams competed under the FIRS rules at The World Roller Games 2017 in Nanjing, China.<ref name="rollersports.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.rollersports.org/|title=Rolling Up to Tokio 2020|website=Rollersports.org|accessdate=2017-11-01}}</ref> The former Canadian Women's Roller Derby Association worked with the American federation.<ref name=rdaf-can>{{cite web |publisher=Roller Derby Association of Canada |accessdate=2011-10-12 |title=Welcome to the CWRDA |url=http://www.cwrda.ca/ |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026035120/http://www.cwrda.ca/ |archivedate=2011-10-26}}</ref>
===Tournaments=== Since 2006, the WFTDA has sponsored an annual championship. In 2008, it took the current [[WFTDA Championship|"Big 5"]] format: four regional playoffs and a final championship tournament.<ref>{{cite web|title=THE BIG 5 WFTDA SPONSORED TOURNAMENTS |url=http://wftda.com/The-Big-5 |publisher=WFTDA |accessdate=2011-11-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111115205158/http://wftda.com/The-Big-5|archivedate=2011-11-15}}</ref> The WFTDA also recognizes eligible tournaments hosted by member leagues.<ref>{{cite web|title=WFTDA Recognized Events|url= http://wftda.com/events|publisher=WFTDA|accessdate=2011-11-15}}</ref> Internationally, the first [[Roller Derby World Cup]] took place in Toronto, Canada, in December 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blood & Thunder Roller Derby World Cup 2011|url=http://bloodandthundermag.com/WorldCup2011.htm|publisher=Blood & Thunder Magazine|accessdate=2011-08-08}}</ref> The [[2014 Roller Derby World Cup|second World Cup]] took place in Dallas, Texas, in December 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dallas to Host 2014 Roller Derby World Cup|url=http://www.rollerderbyworldcup.com/2013/06/10/dallas-to-host-2014-roller-derby-world-cup/|publisher=Blood & Thunder Magazine|date=2013-06-10|accessdate=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214162640/http://www.rollerderbyworldcup.com/2013/06/10/dallas-to-host-2014-roller-derby-world-cup/|archive-date=2014-12-14|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Since 2012, USARS has held an annual Roller Derby National Championship. In 2017, FIRS and the USOC recognized USARS to participate in the Nanjing games.<ref name="rollersports.org"/>
==Social significance== Zaina Arafat asserts in ''[[Virginia Quarterly Review]]'' that roller derby defies [[heteronormativity]] and patriarchal standards. In [[Egypt]], Arafat says, there are expectations that a woman will not show visible scars, will have an unblemished body for her husband, and will refrain from activities that may damage her body. She says roller derby in Egypt is subversive, as it acts as an indirect political statement.<ref>Arafat, Zaina, "POWER JAM: Roller Derby as Political Act", ''[[Virginia Quarterly Review]],'' vol. 93, no. 3, Summer2017, pp. 36-59.</ref>
Carly Giesler states that skaters enact sexualities that create or reclaim an identity, and their role parodies "hegemonic scripts of sexuality" through the use of costumes, derby names and personas. Roller derby acts as a unique stage for female athletes, letting them rebut constraints society places on women and female athletes. Giesler argues that female sports objectifies them for the [[Male gaze|male gaze]], but roller derby turns this on its head by disregarding gender roles and norms.<ref name="gieseler">Gieseler, Carly. “Derby Drag: Parodying Sexualities in the Sport of Roller Derby.” Sexualities, vol. 17, no. 5-6, 2014, pp. 758–776., doi:10.1177/1363460714531268.</ref>
